div.div:
Lux optimizes range comparisons (=, !=, <, <=, >, >=, eq, ne, gt, ge, le, lt) when one of the operands is a constant, and the other is a call to lux:key() or can be proven to match an indexed expression. For example, if there is a string-valued index called "book-id" on
//book/@id, the expression
//book[@id="isbn9780123456789"] would be optimized into something like:
lux:search("book-id:isbn9780123456789"), and evaluated using indexed lookup. There will be additional clauses to the generated query, such as path constraints. Also, equality tests may be optimized using the built-in full text indexes. In the example above, a word-based query such as:
<@id:isbn9780123456789 would be generated, which would find the given isbn, ignoring text normalizations such as case, in any id attribute. These text queries are less selective than the query based on the XPath index, but can often be selective enough, depending on the structure of the documents.
